# Refactor an ARBITRARY sim into the GLOBAL SHELL

You are taking **one simulation HTML file with an unknown / non-standard layout**
(scraped from the web, an open-source sketch, or a one-off) and re-housing it in the
project's shared global shell. The source may be a raw `<canvas>` loop, a p5.js /
three.js sketch, an SVG/DOM animation, or a single-file mess with inline buttons.
Your job: **keep the simulation's physics and visual output exactly as they are**,
and rebuild only the *chrome and layout* around them so it matches every other sim.

This is a **re-housing**, not a redesign of the science. When the source already has
`#shell` + a `Shell = (function(){…})()` runtime, STOP — that's a targeted upgrade;
use `convert-to-global-design.mdc` instead.

## Reference material — read these FIRST, every run (they are ground truth)
- `_design-reference/SHELL-DESIGN-GUIDE.md` — the full spec: layout, anatomy
  mapping, runtime contract, stepper authoring, components, pedagogy rules.
- `_design-reference/reference-converted-sim.html` — a fully converted sim. This is
  the canonical source for the exact markup, the **verbatim `Shell` runtime**, the
  base64 font block, the info modal, and the guided-inquiry stepper. **When anything
  below is ambiguous, copy from this file byte-for-byte.**
- `_design-reference/simulation-shell.css` — the global stylesheet (drop-in; never
  edit it per sim).
- Any existing `*-shell.html` in `shell-versions/` is a good secondary example.

## THE #1 RULE — do not touch the science
- **NEVER change the physics or the rendering.** Equations, constants, numerical
  integration, the draw/render functions, and the pixels they produce must be
  **identical** to the original. You restructure the DOM/CSS around them and rewire
  the *animation transport* only.
- **Preserve every control's behaviour.** Each slider / toggle / button that drives
  the sim must still exist and do exactly what it did — you only move it into its new
  home and restyle the wrapper. **Keep the exact element IDs the sim's JS reads**
  (rename wrappers, never the `<input>`/`<canvas>` the code queries).
- If a layout change can't be made without editing physics/draw code, STOP, leave
  that part as-is, and note it in the report.

