## PHASE 2 — Paste the Shell runtime verbatim

Copy the entire `const Shell = (function(){ … })();` IIFE **verbatim** from
`_design-reference/reference-converted-sim.html` (spec copy in `SHELL-DESIGN-GUIDE.md`
§4) into a `<script>` before your SIM code. **Never edit it** — it owns the animation
loop, Play/Pause, Reset, Speed, Maximize, theme, info modal, panel collapse, and the
whole guided-inquiry stepper (dots, Next/Finish, Skip, restore). You only supply the
four hooks and the content.

---

## PHASE 3 — Rewire the animation loop to the hooks

Implement `Shell.init({ onFrame, onReset, onResize, onStep })` (see §5). Delete the
source's own transport (its Play/Pause/Reset/Speed handlers and its self-driven
loop). Map the loop by framework:

- **Vanilla `requestAnimationFrame` loop:** move the body into `onFrame(dt)` and
  delete the source's `requestAnimationFrame(loop)` bootstrap. `dt` arrives already
  speed-scaled and clamped (seconds) — replace any hard-coded per-frame step or the
  sim's own `dt`/timestamp math with the supplied `dt`.
- **`setInterval` / `setTimeout` loop:** clear the interval; advance the same state
  inside `onFrame(dt)` instead.
- **p5.js:** call `noLoop()` in `setup()`, and drive it from
  `onFrame(dt){ /* advance state */ redraw(); }` (p5's `draw()` becomes pure render).
  Keep p5's `windowResized`/canvas-fit logic reachable from `onResize()`.
- **three.js:** move the contents of the `animate()` render call into `onFrame(dt)`
  (do the `renderer.render(scene,camera)` there); handle DPR/resize in `onResize()`.
- **SVG/DOM/CSS animation:** advance the tweened attributes inside `onFrame(dt)`.

Then:
- `onReset()` — restore all state to defaults and render once. (The shell forces Play
  on after Reset, so Reset doubles as replay.)
- `onResize()` — re-fit the render surface (DPR + `getBoundingClientRect`) and redraw.
  The shell calls this on maximize, panel collapse, theme switch, inquiry collapse,
  and viewport resize — so all canvas sizing must run here.
- A slider drag that should scrub while paused calls `Shell.setPlaying(false)` then
  redraws.
- If the sim is a **static, slider-driven diagram with no honest time-evolution**,
  omit `onFrame` (and drop Play/Speed) — do not invent motion (see Physics honesty).

---

## PHASE 4 — Controls + stats → design-system components

Rebuild the source's controls inside `#aside-controls` using `.shell-panel` cards and
the component classes from §7 (`.ctrl-box ctrl-box--slider` for sliders,
`.ctrl-box` + `.stat-row` for toggles/readouts). Rules:
- **Keep the exact `<input>`/`<select>` IDs** the sim's JS references; only the
  wrapper markup and styling change, so every existing listener keeps firing.
- Every readout the source showed must still appear (in a `.stat-row`).
- Label physical quantities with frame + units ("v = 0.87c (ground frame)"), not a
  bare ratio.
- Panels collapse on head-click (shell-wired). Controls must be live from first paint.

---

## PHASE 5 — Guided inquiry (author 4–6 step cards)

Fill `#inq-cards` with `<div class="inq-step">` cards, one per step, per §6. You write
**only the cards** — the shell builds the dots and drives Next/Finish/Skip/restore.
- If the source had a **prediction/quiz**, convert its exact wording into the cards.
  If it had none, author a short arc from the sim's own concept: predict (gated,
  `data-gate`) → observe → verify (gated) → next layer/frame → resolve.
- **Encode any misconception as a wrong `<button class="choice" data-correct="0"
  data-fb="…">`**; the correct choice is `data-correct="1"`. Add a
  `<div class="predict-eval"></div>` to each predict card. **Never** write a standing
  "common misconception" text card.
- Evolve the scene per step via `onStep(i)` (and read `Shell.step` in draw), not by
  hiding cards.
- Add the generic prediction-feedback handler + its CSS from §6 to the SIM JS.
- Do NOT invent new physics claims — keep the pedagogy the source already implied.
- If there is genuinely no inquiry, leave `#inq-cards` empty; the shell hides the zone.

